<section xml:id="sec-writing-linear-scales-in-ratio-form">
    <title>Writing Linear Scales in Ratio Form</title>
    <activity>
        <p>
            <m>
            \textbf{Materials needed;}
            </m>
            
        </p>
        <p>
            <ul>
                <li>
                    <p>
                        Rulers
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li>
                    <p>
                        String or measuring tapes
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li>
                    <p>
                        Atlases or printed simple maps (or teacher-prepared maps)
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li>
                    <p>
                        Calculators
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li>
                    <p>
                        Manilla paper and markers
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li>
                    <p>
                        Conversion tables (optional handout)
                    </p>
                </li>
            </ul>
            <ol>
                <li>
                    <p>
                        Collection of maps and atlases and distributing to individual groups.
                    </p>
                    <p>
                        (a) Students will work in pairs or small groups to find a map that has a scale. 
                    </p>
                    <p>
                        Choose the Key to use on the Map e.g:
                    </p>
                    <p>
                        1 cm represents 500 m
                    </p>
                    <p>
                        2 cm represents 1 km
                    </p>
                    <p>
                        1.5 cm represents 3.5 km etc.
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li>
                    <p>
                        Convert real distances into cm
                    </p>
                    <p> (a) Write and simplify the ratio e.g 1 cm : 500 m </p>
                    <p> (b) 1 cm : 500 m = 1 : 50,000 </p>
                </li>
                <li>
                    <p>
                        Measure the distance between two landmarks on the map using a ruler or string.
                    </p>
                    <p> (a) If the scale is 1:50,000</p>
                    <p> (b)  Find the real-life distance <m> (3.2 \times 50,000 = 160,000\, \text{cm} = 1.6\, \text{km})</m> </p>
                </li>
                <li>
                    <p>
                        Create a Poster Presentation. Let each group design a poster with:
                    </p>
                    <p>
                      (a)  The original map snippet
                    </p>
                    <p> (b) The converted scales in ratio form</p>
                    <p> (c) Sample calculations</p>
                    <p> (d) A unique name for the map</p>
                </li>
                <li>
                    <p>
                        Gallery Walk and Peer Review 
                    </p>
                    <p>Walk around other groups viewing each other's work and compare their posters posters with yours.</p>
                </li>


            </ol>
        </p>
        <p>
            PART A:  Fill in the table below:
        </p>
        <table>
            <title>Understanding Scale</title>
            <tabular halign="left" valign="top" right="medium" left="medium" top="medium" bottom="medium">
                <row header="yes">
                    <cell>Given Scale (e.g. 1 cm represents 2 km)</cell>
                    <cell>	Convert real-life distance to cm</cell>
                    <cell>Write Ratio Form (same units)</cell>
                </row>
                <row>
                    <cell>1 cm represents 500 m</cell>
                    <cell>____________________________</cell>
                    <cell>____________________________</cell>
                </row>
                <row>
                    <cell>2 cm represents 1 km</cell>
                    <cell>____________________________</cell>
                    <cell>____________________________</cell>
                </row>  
                <row>
                    <cell>1.5 cm represents 3.5 km</cell>
                    <cell>____________________________</cell>
                    <cell>____________________________</cell>
                </row>  
            </tabular>
        </table>
        <p>PART B: Measuring Map Distances</p>
        <p>Use a ruler or string to measure the distance between two landmarks on the map.  Write the distance in cm and calculate their actual real-life distances.</p>
        <table>
            <title>Measuring Map Distances</title>
            <tabular halign="left" valign="top" right="medium" left="medium" top="medium" bottom="medium">
                <row header="yes">
                    <cell>From</cell>
                    <cell>To</cell>
                    <cell>Map Distance (cm)</cell>
                    <cell>
                        Scale used (e.g. 1 cm represents 2 km)
                    </cell>
                    <cell>Actual Distance (km)</cell>
                </row>
                <row>
                    <cell>School</cell>
                    <cell>PLayground</cell>
                    <cell></cell>
                    <cell></cell>
                    <cell></cell>
                </row>
                <row>
                    <cell>Market</cell>
                    <cell>Town Hall</cell>
                    <cell></cell>
                    <cell></cell>
                    <cell></cell>
                </row>
                <row>
                    <cell>Hospital</cell>
                    <cell>Library</cell>
                    <cell></cell>
                    <cell></cell>
                    <cell></cell>
                </row>
            </tabular>
        </table>
        <sidebyside>
            <p>
                <ul>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            <m>\textbf{PART C: Poster Creation}</m>
                        </p>
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            Stick your small map or draw it.
                        </p>
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            Write the ratio scales clearly
                        </p>
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            Show sample distance calculations.
                        </p>
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            Give your map a creative title!
                        </p>
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            Add decorations or fun labels.
                        </p>
                    </li>
                </ul>
            </p>
